It's officially in the logbook. I have 2.3 flight hours ^_^
#TeaganAir
If I had to describe to you what it's like to fly in a small aircraft, I would say it's like a mix of a motorcycle/quad and a boat, 4,000 feet in the air.
On the ground, you are immediately very fast. Everything is somewhat unstable on the ground, therefore motorcycle/quad.
And if you didn't know yet: You steer a plane on the ground with your feet, not with the control stick. Rudder pedals and brakes. It's not a car.
In the air it's unstable, and you're drifting a bit. It feels as if you're in a boat on water. You can control it, but sometimes a wave comes and throws you slightly off course, so you have to get used to the sea conditions, only this time in the air.
Another random detail:
Flying is physically demanding. Today, my back and legs hurt as if I had been at the gym.
That's not like a Sunday car trip. It's more of a sport than a walk, in my newly acquired opinion.
A lovely Saturday, my loves. Welcome to 4,000 feet.
Tomorrow I'll go back. Then we'll practice flow separation and slow flying.
Today the weather was unsettled, but it was a lot of fun. We practiced slow flying and stream breaks. Once we had a ground speed of only 16 mph with an airspeed of 65.
It was a beautiful clear day, somewhat misty a bit higher up, but still beautiful.
FlightAware Data Track.
FlightAware Data Track.
It's really like going to the gym. I took two hours for a nap today (just woke up), because I'm physically exhausted. I also have a pretty bad muscle ache, especially in my legs. A LOT of right-side rowing today.
I need a headset.
Good that the affordable option is available ($699)
